 Bead, contributors address the historical denial of Métis concerns and claims with respect to land, resources, and governance. Tackling such themes as the invisibility of Métis women in court decisions, identity politics, and racist legal principles, they uncover the troubling issues that plague Métis aspirations for a just future. This nuanced analysis of the parameters that current Indigenous legal doctrines place around Métis rights discourse moves beyond a one-size-fits-all approach. By revealing the complexity and diversity of Métis identities and lived reality, it opens new pathways to respectful, inclusive Métis-Canadian constitutional relationships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConstitutional lawzCanada. 0aMétisxCivil rights. 0aMétisxGovernment relations. 0aMétisxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aMétisxSocial conditions. 0aM©♭tisxLegal status, laws, etc. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aBelcourt, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyer, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChartrand, Larry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aChartrand, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Brodie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrake, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGall, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaudry, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrammond, Sébastien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunn, Brenda L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsaac, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul